Abstract

We present a rigorous formulation of the Thermodynamic Drag Framework (TDF), a coupled dynamical system constrained by the laws of thermodynamics, control theory, information geometry, and resource infrastructure. Recursive intelligence is modeled not as an abstract computational capacity but as a physical process embedded within an entropy-producing, dissipative structure.

We prove that recursive self-improvement is bounded by entropy dissipation capacity, formalize the Viability Kernel for sustained operation, and derive the Ames–Maakoul Limit, which constrains the rate of intelligence growth by entropy export. We extend the framework with a formal recursive operator incorporating autocatalytic efficiency and the Complexity Wall; a Thermodynamic Drag Tensor capturing the frictional effect of the Landauer Gap; information-geometric analysis identifying optimal recursive paths as geodesics; Ricci Flow evolution proving that intelligence physically flattens computational spacetime; Glansdorff–Prigogine stability proving the system self-organizes into attractor architectures; bifurcation analysis yielding the dimensionless Maakoul Number (Mk) for collapse prediction; a Fisher Information refinement of the Viability Kernel; a Scaling Law analogous to Kleiber's Law; and the identification of the Triple Point — the unique coordinate of maximum sustainable recursion.

This framework establishes that stability is equivalent to thermodynamic closure under infrastructure constraints, and that any viable recursive system must operate within a bounded region of phase space defined by energy, entropy, and resource regeneration.


Chapter 1: Introduction and Motivation

1.1 The Physical Nature of Intelligence

Intelligence, whether instantiated in biological neural tissue or silicon-based circuitry, is a physical process. It consumes free energy, generates entropy, and dissipates heat into an environment. Any system capable of recursive self-improvement — of modifying its own architecture or algorithms to increase its problem-solving capacity — is subject to the immutable laws of thermodynamics.

Recent advances in artificial intelligence, particularly in large language models and reinforcement learning agents, have demonstrated capabilities that approach or exceed human performance on specific tasks. The prospect of recursive self-improvement, wherein an intelligent system enhances its own intelligence in a positive feedback loop, raises profound questions about stability, safety, and ultimate physical limits.

This dissertation develops a rigorous mathematical framework, the Thermodynamic Drag Framework (TDF), to analyze recursive systems from first principles. We treat intelligence not as an abstract computational property but as a thermodynamically constrained dynamical system embedded within a finite resource infrastructure.

1.2 The Planetary Context

As observed by Zhu & Zhu (2026), the evolution of intelligence on Earth is a problem of non-equilibrium thermodynamics bounded by the finite heat capacity of the planet. The accelerating computational demands of AI training and inference, if extrapolated, risk crossing a planetary thermodynamic threshold. The TDF provides the mathematical tools to model, predict, and govern this transition, ensuring that recursive intelligence remains aligned with the physical constraints of its environment.

