Chapter 2: Mathematical Preliminaries

2.1 State Space Definition

Definition 2.1 (State Manifold). The state of a recursive system is defined on the differentiable manifold:

\mathcal{M} = \mathcal{S} \times \mathcal{I} \times \mathcal{E} \times \Sigma

with state vector:

\Xi(t) = (S(t), I(t), E(t), \Sigma(t))

where:

· $S(t) \in \mathbb{R}^+$: algorithmic / structural complexity (related to Kolmogorov complexity),
· $I(t) \in \mathbb{R}^+$: information density (bits per unit volume),
· $E(t) \in \mathbb{R}^+$: internal energy,
· $\Sigma(t) \in \mathbb{R}^+$: system entropy.

Definition 2.2 (Resource Space). The resource vector is defined as:

R(t) = (E_{\text{avail}}(t), W(t), L(t))

where:

· $E_{\text{avail}}(t)$: usable energy supply rate (power),
· $W(t)$: cooling capacity (water flow rate or equivalent heat removal capacity),
· $L(t)$: spatial infrastructure extent.

2.2 Compute Mapping and Negentropy

Definition 2.3 (Compute Mapping). The computational capacity is given by a monotonic mapping:

C(t) = \Phi(S(t))

with $\Phi: \mathbb{R}^+ \to \mathbb{R}^+$ and $\Phi'(S) > 0$.

Definition 2.4 (Negentropy). Negentropy, the available low-entropy resource, is defined as:

N(t) = -k_B \Sigma(t)

where $k_B$ is the Boltzmann constant.

2.3 Notational Conventions

Throughout this work, we use:

· $\dot{x} = dx/dt$ for time derivatives.
· $\nabla$ for the covariant derivative on $\mathcal{M}$.
· Einstein summation convention for repeated indices.
· $\mathbb{E}[\cdot]$ for expectation.

