Chapter 3: Thermodynamic Foundations

3.1 Landauer's Principle

Theorem 3.1 (Landauer's Principle). Any logically irreversible manipulation of information, such as the erasure of one bit, must be accompanied by a minimum entropy increase of:

\Delta \Sigma \ge k_B \ln 2

in the environment. Equivalently, the minimum heat dissipated is $\Delta Q \ge k_B T \ln 2$.

Proof. See Landauer (1961). The proof follows from the fact that information erasure reduces the number of accessible microstates by a factor of two, requiring a compensating increase in environmental entropy to satisfy the Second Law. ∎

3.2 Entropy Generation and Flux

Definition 3.1 (Entropy Generation Rate). The total entropy generation rate is decomposed as:

\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{gen}} = \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{comp}} + \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{infra}} \ge 0

where $\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{comp}}$ is the entropy production due to computation and $\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{infra}}$ is the entropy production due to infrastructure overhead (cooling, power delivery, etc.).

Definition 3.2 (Entropy Flux). The rate at which entropy is exported to the environment is $\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}$. The entropy balance equation is:

\frac{d\Sigma}{dt} = \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{gen}} - \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}

3.3 Temperature Coupling

The system temperature $T$ depends on computational load and cooling capacity:

T = T(R, C), \quad \frac{\partial T}{\partial C} > 0, \quad \frac{\partial T}{\partial W} < 0

3.4 Extended First Law with Complexity

Following Neukart & Vinokur (2025), we extend the first law of thermodynamics to include a complexity coordinate:

dE = T d\Sigma - p dV + \mu dN + \lambda dC

where $C(t)$ is the computational complexity class (e.g., circuit depth or algorithmic complexity) and $\lambda$ is the conjugate potential—the algorithmic tension. This extension formalizes the idea that increasing algorithmic complexity incurs a fundamental thermodynamic cost.

