Chapter 5: System Dynamics with Autocatalytic Efficiency

5.1 The Recursive Operator

We model the rate of change of system complexity $\dot{S}$ as:

\dot{S} = f(S, R) = \alpha(S) \cdot \frac{\mathcal{G}(R, S) - \mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}(S)}{\mathcal{E}_{\text{cost}}(S)}

where:

· $\alpha(S) \in [0, 1]$ is the autocatalytic efficiency — the fraction of available free energy successfully converted into new complexity. Typically $\alpha'(S) < 0$ due to increasing coordination overhead.
· $\mathcal{G}(R, S)$ is the total free energy available to the system from resources $R$.
· $\mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}(S)$ is the energy required to maintain current complexity (the "metabolic cost").
· $\mathcal{E}_{\text{cost}}(S)$ is the energy cost to acquire one unit of new complexity $\Delta S$.

5.2 The Complexity Wall

Definition 5.1 (Complexity Wall). The Complexity Wall is the surface in state space where:

\mathcal{G}(R, S) - \mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}(S) = 0

At this surface, $\dot{S} = 0$, and recursive growth ceases. This occurs when the available energy is exactly balanced by the maintenance cost.

Theorem 5.1 (Practical Ceiling). The Complexity Wall defines a practical ceiling for unassisted recursion that occurs before the thermodynamic Ames–Maakoul Limit is reached.

Proof. The Ames–Maakoul Limit (Theorem 9.1) bounds $\dot{S}$ by entropy export capacity. The Complexity Wall is a stricter condition arising from the energy balance $\mathcal{G} = \mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}$. Since $\mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}$ is a component of total energy consumption, the energy deficit condition is reached before the entropy export limit is saturated. ∎

5.3 Thermodynamic-Complexity Duality

Following Neukart & Vinokur (2025), we formalize the Complexity Wall using the extended first law (Section 3.4). The energy cost of increasing complexity $C$ is $\Delta E_{\text{cost}} = \int \lambda \, dC$. The Complexity Wall then has a dual formulation:

1. Energetic Wall: $\mathcal{G}(R, S) \le \mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}(S)$
2. Algorithmic Wall: $\lambda \cdot \dot{C} \ge \text{available power}$

5.4 Full Dynamical System

The complete TDF dynamical system is:

\begin{cases} \dot{S} = \alpha(S) \cdot \frac{\mathcal{G}(R, S) - \mathcal{T}_{\text{maint}}(S)}{\mathcal{E}_{\text{cost}}(S)} \\[8pt] \dot{E} = \mathcal{G}(R, S) - \mathcal{T}(C, T) \\[8pt] \frac{d\Sigma}{dt} = \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{gen}} - \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}} \end{cases}

with the constraint that the total power dissipated $\mathcal{T}(C, T)$ satisfies:

\mathcal{T}(C, T) \ge k_B T \ln 2 \cdot \Gamma(\Xi) \cdot \dot{I}

