Chapter 6: Information-Geometric Formulation

6.1 Fisher Information Metric on the State Manifold

We equip the state manifold $\mathcal{M}$ with a Riemannian metric derived from the distinguishability of thermodynamic states.

Definition 6.1 (Fisher Information Metric). The Fisher Information Metric on $\mathcal{M}$ is defined as:

g_{\mu\nu}^F(\Xi) = \mathbb{E}\left[ \frac{\partial \log p(\text{data} \mid \Xi)}{\partial \Xi^\mu} \frac{\partial \log p(\text{data} \mid \Xi)}{\partial \Xi^\nu} \right]

where $p(\text{data} \mid \Xi)$ is the probability distribution over observable data given the system state $\Xi$. In a thermodynamic context, $p$ corresponds to the probability distribution over microstates given the macroscopic state variables.

6.2 Geodesics as Optimal Paths

Theorem 6.1 (Optimal Recursive Path). The optimal recursive trajectory minimizing entropy production between two states $\Xi_1$ and $\Xi_2$ is a geodesic on $(\mathcal{M}, g_{\mu\nu}^F)$.

Proof. The total entropy produced along a path $\gamma$ is proportional to the thermodynamic action:

\mathcal{A}[\gamma] = \int_\gamma \sqrt{g_{\mu\nu}^F \dot{\Xi}^\mu \dot{\Xi}^\nu} \, dt

By the principle of least action, the path that minimizes this functional satisfies the geodesic equation:

\ddot{\Xi}^\mu + \Gamma^\mu_{\alpha\beta} \dot{\Xi}^\alpha \dot{\Xi}^\beta = 0

where $\Gamma^\mu_{\alpha\beta}$ are the Christoffel symbols of $g_{\mu\nu}^F$. ∎

6.3 Information-Geometric Distance

Definition 6.2 (Thermodynamic Distance). The minimum thermodynamic work required to transition from $\Xi_1$ to $\Xi_2$ is proportional to the geodesic distance:

d(\Xi_1, \Xi_2) = \inf_{\gamma} \int_{\gamma} \sqrt{g_{\mu\nu}^F d\Xi^\mu d\Xi^\nu}

This distance measures the intrinsic difficulty of the state transition.

