Chapter 7: Dissipative Structure Stability

7.1 The Glansdorff–Prigogine Criterion

The TDF system is an open, dissipative structure. Stability can be analyzed using the Glansdorff–Prigogine (G-P) criterion.

Theorem 7.1 (Glansdorff–Prigogine Stability Criterion). A non-equilibrium steady state of a dissipative system is stable if:

\frac{d_X P}{dt} \le 0

where $P = \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{gen}}$ is the total entropy production, and $d_X P$ is the change in entropy production due solely to changes in the thermodynamic forces (gradients).

Proof. See Glansdorff & Prigogine (1971). The proof follows from Lyapunov stability theory applied to the entropy balance equation. ∎

7.2 Attractor Architectures

Corollary 7.1 (Attractor Architectures). The shape of stable recursive intelligence is not arbitrary; it is a specific attractor in the space of algorithmic structures that minimizes entropy production under given resource constraints.

Implication: The TDF predicts that viable self-improving systems will converge to architectures that are geometrically "flat" in the sense of minimal Thermodynamic Drag.

7.3 Information-Geometric Generalization

To address known limitations of the G-P criterion, we adopt the information-geometric generalization (Ito, 2018). The stability condition becomes:

\frac{d}{dt} \left( \int_{\mathcal{M}} \sqrt{\det g^F} \, d\Xi \right) \le 0

This formulation is valid for arbitrary nonlinear master equations and integrates naturally with the Fisher Information Metric.

