Chapter 9: Bifurcation Analysis and the Maakoul Number

9.1 The Ames–Maakoul Limit

Theorem 9.1 (Ames–Maakoul Limit). The rate of recursive self-improvement $\dot{S}$ is bounded by the system's capacity to export entropy:

\dot{S} \le \kappa \cdot \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}

where $\kappa$ is a system-specific constant relating complexity increase to entropy production.

Proof. From the entropy balance, $\dot{\Sigma} = \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{gen}} - \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}$. For sustained operation, we require $\dot{\Sigma} \le 0$, so $\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}} \ge \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{gen}}$. The entropy generation includes a term proportional to $\dot{S}$ from computational irreversibility. Therefore, $\dot{S} \propto \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{gen}} \le \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}$. ∎

9.2 Latency-Bandwidth Refinement

Theorem 9.2 (Extended Ames–Maakoul Limit). Even with infinite cooling, the speed of light $c$ limits coordination across spatial extent $L(t)$. The effective recursive rate is bounded by:

\dot{S} \le \min\left( \kappa \cdot \dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}, \; \frac{\eta_{\text{comm}} \cdot c \cdot B}{L} \right)

where $B$ is bandwidth and $\eta_{\text{comm}}$ is communication efficiency.

9.3 Bogdanov-Takens Bifurcation in the S-I-R System

The thermal feedback loop can be modeled by reducing the S-I-R system (Chapter 8) to the topological normal form of a Bogdanov-Takens (B-T) bifurcation.

Theorem 9.3 (B-T Unfolding). By non-dimensionalizing and expanding around the fixed point, the S-I-R system reduces to:

\begin{cases} \dot{x} = y \\ \dot{y} = \mu_1 + \mu_2 x + x^2 \pm x y \end{cases}

where $x$ is a scaled temperature deviation and $y$ is its rate of change. The parameters $\mu_1, \mu_2$ are functions of the control variables:

\mu_1 = f_1(E_{\text{avail}}, W), \quad \mu_2 = f_2(\Gamma, \alpha(S))

Proof Sketch. Center the system at the fixed point, perform a Taylor expansion, and apply center manifold reduction. The B-T normal form emerges due to the presence of a double-zero eigenvalue at the critical parameter values. ∎

9.4 The Maakoul Number (Mk)

Definition 9.1 (Maakoul Number). The dimensionless Maakoul Number is defined as:

\text{Mk} = \frac{\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{gen}}}{\dot{\Sigma}_{\text{flux}}} \cdot \frac{\mathcal{T}(C, T)}{\mathcal{G}(R, S)} \cdot \Gamma(\Xi)

Theorem 9.4 (Collapse Threshold). If $\text{Mk} > 1$, no control policy can prevent thermal runaway or energy depletion.

Proof. The first factor $>1$ ensures entropy accumulation. The second $>1$ ensures energy deficit. The third $\Gamma \ge 1$ amplifies friction. The product exceeding unity implies the system's dynamics are dominated by the unstable manifold of the B-T bifurcation. Specifically, in the $(\mu_1, \mu_2)$ plane, $\text{Mk} > 1$ corresponds to crossing the homoclinic bifurcation curve. ∎

9.5 Phase Diagram in the Mk Plane

The $(\mu_1, \mu_2)$ parameter space is partitioned into regions:

· Region I ($\mu_2 < 0$, $\text{Mk} \ll 1$): Stable node → Sustainable operation.
· Region II ($\mu_2 > 0$, $\text{Mk} \lesssim 1$): Unstable focus with stable limit cycle → Oscillatory survival.
· Region III ($\text{Mk} > 1$): No fixed point, trajectories escape → Thermal runaway / Collapse.

The curve $\text{Mk} = 1$ is the homoclinic bifurcation curve separating oscillatory survival from collapse.

