Chapter 10: Viability Theory and the Fisher-Refined Kernel

10.1 Viability Kernel Definition

Definition 10.1 (Viability Kernel). The Viability Kernel $K$ is the largest subset of state space $\mathcal{M}$ within which there exists a control policy that keeps the system trajectory for all time under all admissible disturbances.

10.2 Fisher-Refined Viability Kernel

We refine the kernel using the Fisher Information Metric to ensure the system maintains sufficient self-awareness.

Definition 10.2 (Fisher-Refined Viability Kernel).

K_F = \left\{ \Xi \in \mathcal{M} \;\middle|\; E \ge E_{\min}, \; \Sigma \le \Sigma_{\max}, \; \det(g_{\mu\nu}^F) \ge \theta_{\min} \right\}

The condition $\det(g^F) \ge \theta_{\min}$ ensures the system has sufficient Fisher Information about its own state to navigate the thermodynamic landscape. A system with low Fisher Information drifts from geodesic paths and exits the kernel faster.

10.3 Hamilton-Jacobi-Isaacs Formulation

The Viability Kernel can be characterized as the zero sublevel set of a value function $V(\Xi)$ solving the Hamilton-Jacobi-Isaacs (HJI) equation:

\min_{u \in U} \max_{d \in D} \left[ \nabla V \cdot \dot{\Xi}(\Xi, u, d) \right] = 0

where $u$ are control actions (throttling, cooling allocation) and $d$ are disturbances (load spikes, ambient temperature rises).

