Chapter 11: Stochastic Dynamics and Large Deviations

11.1 Stochastic Differential Equation Formulation

In the presence of thermal and resource fluctuations, the dynamics become stochastic:

d\Xi^\mu = f^\mu(\Xi, R) \, dt + \sigma^\mu_\nu(\Xi) \, dW^\nu_t

where $W_t$ is a Wiener process and $\sigma$ is the noise amplitude matrix.

11.2 Freidlin-Wentzell Large Deviation Theory

Theorem 11.1 (Expected Exit Time). Under small noise $\epsilon$, the expected time $\tau_{\text{exit}}$ for the system to first exit the Viability Kernel $K_F$ is:

\tau_{\text{exit}} \asymp \exp\left( \frac{V_0}{\epsilon} \right)

where $V_0$ is the quasi-potential barrier height — the minimum action required to leave $K_F$.

Proof. See Freidlin & Wentzell (2012). The proof uses the large deviation principle for diffusion processes. ∎

11.3 Fluctuation Theorems and Recursive Risk

Theorem 11.2 (Crooks Fluctuation Theorem for TDF). The ratio of probabilities of forward growth ($\Delta S > 0$) to backward regression ($-\Delta S$) satisfies:

\frac{P(\Delta S)}{P(-\Delta S)} = \exp\left( \frac{\Delta \Sigma_{\text{total}}}{k_B} \right)

where $\Delta \Sigma_{\text{total}}$ is the total entropy produced along the forward path.

Implication: Near the Ames–Maakoul limit, $\Delta \Sigma_{\text{total}}$ is small, implying a non-negligible probability of spontaneous recursive regression. This defines a fundamental Risk of Unlearning that must be managed.

