Chapter 12: Scaling Laws and the Complexity Wall

12.1 TDF Scaling Law (Kleiber's Analogue)

Hypothesis 12.1 (TDF Scaling Law). The free energy required to maintain complexity $S$ scales as:

\mathcal{G}(R, S) \propto S^\beta

where $\beta$ is the scaling exponent.

12.2 Interpretation of the Scaling Exponent

· $\beta < 1$ (Sublinear): Larger systems are more efficient per unit complexity. TDF is scalable.
· $\beta = 1$ (Linear): Neutral scaling.
· $\beta > 1$ (Superlinear): Infrastructure must grow faster than complexity. This implies a hard thermodynamic ceiling for unassisted recursive systems.

Empirical data from data center scaling suggests $\beta \approx 1.2–1.4$ for current architectures, indicating that recursive systems without fundamental thermodynamic innovation are inherently unstable at large scales.

12.3 The Complexity Wall Revisited

The Complexity Wall (Section 5.2) occurs when $\dot{S} = 0$. With the scaling law, this condition becomes:

S_{\max} \propto \left( \frac{\mathcal{G}}{\text{const}} \right)^{1/\beta}

For $\beta > 1$, $S_{\max}$ grows sublinearly with energy input, making large-scale recursion increasingly difficult.

