Chapter 14: The Triple Point

14.1 Definition

Definition 14.1 (Triple Point). A system reaches the Triple Point $\Xi^*$ when its state vector simultaneously satisfies:

1. Kinetic Balance: $\dot{S} > 0$ (Recursive growth is active and positive).
2. Structural Integrity: $\text{Mk} \to 1^-$ (The Maakoul Number approaches unity from below; the system operates at peak efficiency without crossing into thermal runaway).
3. Thermodynamic Efficiency: $\Gamma(\Xi) \to 1$ (The Drag Coefficient approaches the Landauer-limit ideal).

14.2 Quantitative Characterization

The Triple Point $\Xi^*$ is the unique solution to the system:

\begin{cases} f(S^*, R) = 0^+ \quad \text{(marginal positive growth)} \\ \text{Mk}(\Xi^*) = 1^- \\ \Gamma(\Xi^*) = 1 + \varepsilon, \quad \varepsilon \ll 1 \end{cases}

